Attention Parents:
We will be sending out a "School Messanger Opt-In" text message later this week to all parent cell phones that we have on file.

This system is completely optional and will be used for our daily student health screenings as well as alerts for emergencies like school closings, snow days, and school delays. If you do not receive this opt-in text this week, please contact the district and we will add your phone number to our list.

Please use the information below to sign up!

Mandatory Graduation Rehearsal! Wednesday, June 24th at 2:00 PM
(For Graduates ONLY - if you bring family members, they must remain in the car.)

Park in the Main Parking Lot and then head out to the corner of the school property (you should see a stage set up out there).

*Please wear a mask.
*Please stay socially distanced (6 feet apart at all times).
*DO NOT wear your cap and gown to rehearsal.

Please remember - this rehearsal is EXTREMELY important. This venue is new to all of us and we have ONE opportunity to get it right and practiced. So please arrive on time and listen carefully to all instructions.

If you have any questions please contact Mr. Myott or Mr. Endieveri or email info@Argylecsd.org and we will get answers for them.

See you on Wednesday!! #WearetheScots #Classof2020 #SeniorStrong

We are just one week away from the Class of 2020 Outdoor Graduation Ceremony! As we continue to plan the event, we have to tell you that we think this is going to be a really great ceremony - for a really great class!

Like everything these days, there are a number of new rules and guidelines for us to be aware of and follow - while none of us are crazy about all of them, we are determined NOT to let them get in the way of this awesome event! So, as not to put health and safety at risk, and out of respect for our graduates and their ceremony, we are going to make sure we follow all state guidelines. We respectfully request that you and your family do the same.

Included below is a lot of important information and details for you to be aware of. Please, as you read through the info, if you have any questions, please call the school 518-638-8243 ext 301 or email info@Argylecsd.org and we will make sure you get your questions answered. READ MORE: http://www.argylecsd.org/jr__sr_high_school/Graduation_Update_Class_of_2020

We are pleased to announce that the proposed budget for the 2020-2021 school year has been approved!

The results are as follows:
‚Ä¢ The budget passed with 612 yes, 155 no
‚Ä¢ Library Vote passed with 548 yes 218 no
‚Ä¢ Board of Education vote: Tom Genovese was re-elected to a 5-Year term with 611 votes.

Thank you to all community members who participated in the budget vote. We greatly appreciate your continued support of the Argyle School District! #WeAreTheScots

PLEASE READ this important information regarding the 2020-2021 Budget Vote and Board of Education Election.

School Budget Ballots will now be counted on Tuesday, June 16, 2020 beginning at 5 p.m.

Governor Cuomo's Executive Order 202.39 has modified the rules for the District Budget Vote and Board of Education election. Per the order, the District can only accept in-person ballots through 5pm on Tuesday, June 9, 2020. However, ballots delivered by mail will be counted as long as they are received by the district by 5 p.m. on Tuesday, June 16, 2020.
text:
PLEASE READ this important information regarding the 2020-2021 Budget Vote and Board of Education Election.

School Budget Ballots will now be counted on Tuesday, June 16, 2020 beginning at 5 p.m.

Governor Cuomo's Executive Order 202.39 has modified the rules for the District Budget Vote and Board of Education election. Per the order, the District can only accept in-person ballots through 5pm on Tuesday, June 9, 2020. However, ballots delivered by mail will be counted as long as they are received by the district by 5 p.m. on Tuesday, June 16, 2020.

SUNY is excited to announce their first-ever virtual college fairs on Thursday, May 14 from 3p-7p and Saturday, May 16 from 1p-6p! Please register at https://www.suny.edu/attend/events/virtual-college-fair/?fbclid=IwAR2v3dBRD1m5pNYBudHahTAd8g1vvsdSrFC_0BoFdnWy4yBQYasn4jpKgjg
The fair will include representatives from nearly every SUNY campus. During the fair, students will be able to communicate with campus representatives using text and video chat.

This is a unique opportunity to explore all of the opportunities at The State University of New York: challenging academics; innovative research; global study; and financial support.
We hope your juniors and their families will attend.

shared_text:
Adirondack Technical Solutions
March 30 at 2:13 PM ¬∑

We‚Äôre all in this together. Over the weekend, we set up a wireless access point near our office at 5439 State Route 40 [by the intersection of County Route 44 and State Route 40 in Argyle]. This WiFi hotspot features a 50MB fiber internet connection and is free for all students to use to download course materials. The hotspot covers a large parking area and allows for plenty of social distancing.

To join, simply click on the wireless network named ‚ÄúStudents‚Äù. No password is required. In this time of need, we ask that you treat the connection fairly with all other users in mind. The network is monitored closely - please be respectful of others or individual access may be restricted.

If you are having any issues with the connection, please call (518) 638-2020 and we‚Äôd be happy to help out. Please refrain from walking over to our office as our essential employees are working on our critical customer needs.

post_text: Today, our 4th grade students enjoyed a visit with presenters from the Fort Ticonderoga Museum. Students learned about soldier's day to day lives, including what they carried in their knapsacks, how they dressed, what they ate and how they kept themselves entertained at the fort! Lillian McEvoy even got the chance to dress like a solider and feel how heavy soldier's bags were that they carried on their long journeys.

Argyle Central School proudly announces that sophomore Emma Harwood has been selected to attend the Hugh O‚ÄôBrien Youth Leadership Seminar. Emma is the daughter of Mark and Stephanie Harwood. She participates in a variety of extracurricular activities including Basketball; Tennis; Skiing; Younglife; Art Club; Interscholastic Equestrian Association; Vice President of Class and works as a waitress.

Trisha Perkins has been selected as the alternate H.O.B.Y. representative. Trisha is the daughter of Nikita Maurer. She participates in Drama Club and Recycling Club. She volunteers at the Argyle Library and a local animal shelter.

The H.O.B.Y. Foundation was established to give outstanding sophomores the opportunity to interact with recognized leaders in business, government, science, art, and education through workshops designed to develop and stimulate young people‚Äôs leadership abilities. The Seminar will be held in May at SUNY Oneonta.

We are doing a *GIVEAWAY*! The district has been lucky enough to receive a donated season pass to Willard Mountain Ski Area. We have a running list of entries in Mr. Garrison's room for those without Facebook, but we are accepting entries here as well!

Details:
-Transportation to and from the mountain is not provided by the school
-Pass does NOT include equipment rentals
-This is an unlimited season pass for the remainder of this year
-Winner must be a student of Argyle CSD

Please comment below the name of the student you would like to enter. We will be drawing names THIS THURSDAY. We will export all the names on Facebook as well as the students who have entered in person and randomly select a student. Good Luck!

Argyle Central School proudly announces that senior Caleb Flower has been selected as the 2020 Daughters of the American Revolution Good Citizen.

Caleb was nominated by the faculty at Argyle Central and voted by his fellow class members as best exemplifying the characteristics of dependability, service, leadership, and patriotism. He is the son of Duane and Jennifer Flower.

Caleb is very active in school and has participated in a variety of extracurricular activities including Varsity Soccer; Varsity Tennis; Big Brothers/Big Sisters; Natural Helpers; Math Club and Ski Club. He is also a member of the NYS Science Honor Society and National Honor Society.

Argyle Central School takes great pride in selecting a young man of Caleb‚Äôs caliber for such a prestigious award.
